Boston Legal
Season 5, Episode 01

02:59.900 --> 03:01.000
Bethany.

03:01.500 --> 03:02.960
For the last seven years,

03:03.000 --> 03:05.960
I've basically had one case
that's consumed me.

03:06.000 --> 03:09.160
It's against A. B. Curtis,
the the tobacco company.

03:09.200 --> 03:10.360
And how's the family?

03:10.400 --> 03:13.060
These people have dragged me
through discovery.

03:13.100 --> 03:15.960
They've exhausted
my client's money, my money.

03:16.000 --> 03:18.360
They practically killed
my client's doctor.

03:18.400 --> 03:19.900
He's dead, Alan.

03:20.700 --> 03:21.660
He was a smoker?

03:21.700 --> 03:23.800
No, but he was in his 70s.

03:23.800 --> 03:26.200
They deposed him 13 times.

03:26.200 --> 03:27.560
He died over the weekend,

03:27.600 --> 03:29.460
just as we were about
to go to trial,

03:29.500 --> 03:31.360
no doubt from the stress
of it all.

03:31.400 --> 03:33.260
Now I don't have
a doctor to testify.

03:33.300 --> 03:34.860
I'll have to get
a continuance,

03:34.900 --> 03:37.460
which they'll then turn
into ten more continuances

03:37.500 --> 03:40.160
while they depose
my new doctor 13 more times.

03:40.200 --> 03:43.000
I can't do it.
I'm licked.

03:44.500 --> 03:47.600
Nobody successfully sues
a tobacco company.

03:47.700 --> 03:50.460
Even if you beat them
at trial, they just appeal.

03:50.500 --> 03:52.960
Law firms go bankrupt
trying to climb that hill.

03:53.000 --> 03:56.260
Oh, you know how I feel about money,
especially when it's yours.

03:56.300 --> 03:58.960
I must say, I echo Shirley's
sentiment. I do. I do.

03:59.000 --> 04:01.260
Tobacco companies
specialize in two things—

04:01.300 --> 04:02.960
One, getting people
addicted to cigarettes,

04:03.000 --> 04:05.860
and two, prolonging
and protracting pretrial litigation.

04:05.900 --> 04:07.860
I tell you, they simply
make cases too burdensome,

04:07.900 --> 04:09.360
even for big firms like us.

04:09.400 --> 04:12.760
Certainly more than could be
handled by your average dwarf.

04:12.800 --> 04:14.860
I, too, am against taking on
the tobacco company,

04:14.900 --> 04:18.266
and the firm absolutely
forbids you from taking it.

04:18.300 --> 04:21.899
Katie, Jerry, give Alan whatever
help he needs.

04:22.400 --> 04:23.300
Best of luck.

04:23.300 --> 04:24.500
Thank you.

04:25.900 --> 04:28.960
Denny, I could also use your help
if you're up for joining.

04:29.000 --> 04:31.000
Mm. Whatever.

04:36.000 --> 04:37.460
<i>Mr Crane!
Mr Crane!</i>

04:37.500 --> 04:38.460
Mr Shore! Mr Shore!

04:38.500 --> 04:41.200
No comment. Nothing to say.

04:41.200 --> 04:42.900
Step aside, please.

04:43.000 --> 04:45.600
No comment.
Lawyers coming through.

04:45.700 --> 04:47.800
Handicapped.
Outta my way.

05:01.000 --> 05:02.200
Phoebe.

05:02.600 --> 05:03.600
Alan.

05:06.500 --> 05:08.800
Are you joining
as cocounsel?

05:08.800 --> 05:09.800
Yes.

05:10.400 --> 05:11.600
Excellent.

05:15.900 --> 05:19.600
Still married with, uh,
what is it they're called?

05:20.100 --> 05:22.000
–Children.
–Right.

05:22.100 --> 05:23.500
All rise.

05:24.200 --> 05:27.400
“3-2-4-6-3—in the matter
of the estate

05:27.400 --> 05:31.300
of Michael Rhodes vs
A. B. Curtis tobacco corporation,

05:31.300 --> 05:34.160
the complainant alleging
the civil cause of wrongful death,”

05:34.200 --> 05:36.060
this court is now in session,

05:36.100 --> 05:38.800
the honorable
Milton Brody presiding.

05:39.000 --> 05:40.200
Be seated.

05:41.700 --> 05:44.200
Okay. Both sides stand ready?

05:44.200 --> 05:47.760
Well, actually, your honor,
the defense would be requesting more time.

05:47.800 --> 05:50.160
The plaintiff has added
a witness to its list

05:50.200 --> 05:52.460
whom we've not had
the opportunity to depose.

05:52.500 --> 05:53.860
Therefore, I—
–The witness, your honor,

05:53.900 --> 05:57.760
is a doctor who will only be
 testifying as to cause of death.

05:57.800 --> 05:59.600
We are forced to call him

05:59.600 --> 06:01.760
because the doctor
we had planned to call—

06:01.800 --> 06:04.360
who has been called
again and again and again—

06:04.400 --> 06:05.760
died this past weekend

06:05.800 --> 06:09.560
after being deposed, harassed
and intimidated relentlessly

06:09.600 --> 06:12.700
for the last 7
of his 77 years.

06:12.700 --> 06:14.600
The fact is, my, uh…

06:15.200 --> 06:16.600
uh, uh, the defense,

06:16.600 --> 06:18.900
has employed
a plethora of tactics

06:18.900 --> 06:20.900
to delay a delay and delay.

06:20.900 --> 06:24.060
I'm curious. Do you have
any ideas that speed things up?

06:24.100 --> 06:26.160
Well, surrender works
quite well, and I do know

06:26.200 --> 06:28.360
how you love to wave a white flag.
–Objection!

06:28.400 --> 06:30.300
All right. All right.

06:30.400 --> 06:32.560
Ms Prentice,
I will give you a night—

06:32.600 --> 06:34.660
one night—
to review the new witnesses

06:34.700 --> 06:36.660
that have been added
to the plaintiff's list.

06:36.700 --> 06:40.300
We will begin at 10:00 a.m.
Tomorrow. Adjourned.

06:44.800 --> 06:45.500
You know…

06:55.900 --> 06:57.360
Once the cancer had metastasized,

06:57.400 --> 06:59.160
it became about managing his pain,

06:59.200 --> 07:01.200
which was extreme.

07:01.700 --> 07:04.060
Mr Rhodes told you
that he chose to smoke,

07:04.100 --> 07:07.664
am I right, doctor?
–Why, does that make it hurt less?

07:08.100 --> 07:09.400
I'd like to know.

07:10.000 --> 07:11.300
May I continue?

07:12.000 --> 07:13.100
Please.

07:14.000 --> 07:15.860
There were many other
cancer-causing agents

07:15.900 --> 07:17.960
that Mr Rhodes
was exposed to, right?

07:18.000 --> 07:19.660
I'm sorry. Is that going
to be your strategy,

07:19.700 --> 07:21.746
that something else killed him?

07:22.200 --> 07:23.660
We can suspend this
right now, Alan,

07:23.700 --> 07:24.860
and go see the judge

07:24.900 --> 07:26.560
if this is all too much
for you to handle.

07:26.600 --> 07:29.360
–Don't flatter yourself.
–No, I wasn't talking about me.

07:29.400 --> 07:30.700
Funny that you are.

07:30.700 --> 07:31.760
Something on your heart

07:31.800 --> 07:33.460
you'd like to share with
the rest of the group?

07:33.500 --> 07:35.360
I'm sorry. I meant
to say on your mind.

07:35.400 --> 07:36.500
Stop it.

07:36.500 --> 07:39.400
You two can get a room
after the trial.

07:41.800 --> 07:44.900
Uh, was an autopsy
ever performed, doctor?

07:44.900 --> 07:47.860
Oh, we didn't need an autopsy
to know what killed him.

07:47.900 --> 07:49.000
No autopsy.

07:49.000 --> 07:50.600
Are you kidding?

07:51.100 --> 07:51.900
Ms Rhodes—

07:51.900 --> 07:55.900
My father smoked for 50 years.
He died of lung cancer.

07:55.900 --> 07:58.660
Do you really mean to suggest—
–Ma'am, I need to–

07:58.700 --> 08:01.160
Have you ever
watched a person rot to death?

08:01.200 --> 08:04.360
Alan, maybe you can contain
your client's emotions,

08:04.400 --> 08:05.700
if not your own.

08:07.000 --> 08:08.700
What happened to you?

08:10.400 --> 08:11.720
All right. I'm done.

08:13.500 --> 08:16.460
If you plan to march into that courtroom
and ask for a continuance—

08:16.500 --> 08:19.400
No. I got what I need.
Did you?

08:22.000 --> 08:23.000
Thank you.

08:32.000 --> 08:33.360
Is that how you plan
to try this case?

08:33.400 --> 08:35.059
Don't start with me,
Denny. All right?

08:35.100 --> 08:38.559
Do you have any idea how many
people die every day from cigarettes?

08:38.600 --> 08:40.514
Oh, please.
What else is new?

08:40.700 --> 08:43.960
Tobacco kills. Big deal.
–Did you just say “big deal”?

08:44.000 --> 08:45.960
–Well, it's old news.
–First of all,

08:46.000 --> 08:48.660
it's not just old news.
It's absolely current.

08:48.700 --> 08:53.300
The tobacco industry is more powerful today—
–It's boring.

08:54.800 --> 08:57.660
What, have we all just been desensitized?
Smoking kills. Whatever.

08:57.700 --> 08:59.350
We've all just gone numb.

09:02.300 --> 09:03.554
Why'd you say that?

09:04.800 --> 09:07.300
Who told you I went numb?

09:07.400 --> 09:08.800
Who said that?

09:09.000 --> 09:10.260
What are you talking about?

09:10.300 --> 09:12.800
You damn well k—

09:13.400 --> 09:14.260
Did she call you?

09:14.300 --> 09:18.062
Denny, I have no idea
what the hell you're talking about.

09:18.100 --> 09:19.750
So why don't you tell me?

09:20.800 --> 09:22.960
You have been
in a bad mood all day.

09:23.000 --> 09:24.100
What is up?

09:24.100 --> 09:26.700
Nothing's up.
That's the problem.

09:28.200 --> 09:30.000
My junk doesn't work.

09:30.400 --> 09:31.460
I beg your pardon?

09:31.500 --> 09:34.100
I went back
to the captain's quarters

09:34.100 --> 09:36.560
with one of the girls
from the hot tub…

09:36.600 --> 09:39.500
My junk failed me.
–Oh.

09:40.100 --> 09:41.960
–I'm done, Alan, dead.
–Denny—

09:42.000 --> 09:43.600
I wish I were dead.

09:43.700 --> 09:46.360
I'd have made a better showing
with rigor mortis.

09:46.400 --> 09:48.060
I'm dead. Done. It's over.

09:48.100 --> 09:50.600
Denny,
it happens to every guy.

09:51.000 --> 09:52.160
Has it happened to you?

09:52.200 --> 09:53.600
Once.

09:54.000 --> 09:55.584
Shh. Shh. Shh. Shh. Shh.

09:55.600 --> 09:56.600
Hello.

09:57.000 --> 09:58.000
Hello.

09:58.600 --> 10:00.200
How'd the deposition go?

10:00.300 --> 10:02.600
Fine. Why?

10:02.700 --> 10:04.760
There are rumors
you were horrendous.

10:04.800 --> 10:06.800
Alan, I'm happy to support

10:06.800 --> 10:09.100
your latest tilt
at the windmill,

10:09.100 --> 10:11.600
but we know one never really beats

10:11.700 --> 10:13.700
the tobacco industry, right?

10:13.700 --> 10:15.860
And if opportunity
for settlement does come,

10:15.900 --> 10:18.400
we will take it,
won't we?

10:18.500 --> 10:19.900
It's receded…

10:20.900 --> 10:22.400
like a turtle…

10:22.700 --> 10:25.100
too ashamed
to come out its shell.

10:30.000 --> 10:31.100
What?

10:38.400 --> 10:41.900
Shirley, could I, uh,
steal you for a second?

10:42.000 --> 10:43.700
It's about my penis.

10:46.000 --> 10:47.300
It's depressed.

10:47.300 --> 10:51.200
–I-I don't want to involve you, but—
–Don't even go there.

10:51.400 --> 10:53.000
Okay, okay.

10:53.100 --> 10:55.960
Would you at least put on
the cheerleader costume for me?

10:56.000 --> 10:56.860
Because—
–Sorry.

10:56.900 --> 10:58.760
Have you tried jumper cables?

10:58.800 --> 11:00.384
You think this is funny?

11:01.900 --> 11:05.200
Okay. Would you loan me
the cheerleading costume?

11:05.200 --> 11:08.170
–Denny…
–Give me a hand here, will you, Carl?

11:17.500 --> 11:19.360
–Two witnesses total?
–Bethany—

11:19.400 --> 11:22.460
I've spent 7 years preparing
more than 50 experts—

11:22.500 --> 11:23.800
Bethany…

11:23.800 --> 11:25.960
if we let this
turn into a science class—

11:26.000 --> 11:28.860
We have to prove addiction.
We have to show that—

11:28.900 --> 11:31.060
You asked me to try this case.
So let me—

11:31.100 --> 11:33.560
–Two⁈
–I want to rest as close as I can

11:33.600 --> 11:36.400
to the emotion
of the client's test—

11:38.000 --> 11:39.000
Where'd she go?

11:39.000 --> 11:39.900
She left.

11:39.900 --> 11:43.332
I must say, Alan, two witnesses
seems a bit bonkers.

11:43.400 --> 11:45.644
I would hope
you haven't gone mad.

11:46.600 --> 11:50.400
Katie, one problem we have
concerning trust—

11:50.400 --> 11:53.634
You and I haven't really
had a life together yet.

11:53.800 --> 11:56.260
Still harassing
the younger associates?

11:56.300 --> 11:58.800
So nice to see
you haven't changed.

12:03.800 --> 12:05.500
Why are you here?

12:06.000 --> 12:08.400
Well, I come in peace.

12:09.400 --> 12:11.400
$140,000.

12:11.600 --> 12:13.360
–For a death?
–It's all we're offering.

12:13.400 --> 12:16.160
It's all you could hope to get
since we'll appeal any verdict.

12:16.200 --> 12:17.660
And why drag this out beyond a time

12:17.700 --> 12:20.406
we're still attracted to each other, hmm?

12:23.100 --> 12:25.300
I'm not attracted to you now.

12:26.500 --> 12:28.600
Fine. Let's go with that.

12:30.400 --> 12:33.040
When I knew him,
he was mad, by the way.

12:34.000 --> 12:35.500
I think I'll be going.

12:39.300 --> 12:41.800
I have done hundreds
of these cases,

12:41.800 --> 12:43.860
and they all come out
the same way…

12:43.900 --> 12:46.300
So why stress yourself, Alan?

12:46.300 --> 12:49.996
It's not healthy. You'd be
better off taking up smoking.

12:52.900 --> 12:54.360
You know,
the thing is, Phoebe,

12:54.400 --> 12:55.900
you look the same,

12:55.900 --> 12:58.000
you smell the same…

12:58.900 --> 12:59.700
Mm.

13:00.400 --> 13:02.500
My, you even taste the same…

13:04.500 --> 13:08.000
But we both know
you've changed, don't we?

13:09.000 --> 13:10.460
I mean, when
we were together,

13:10.500 --> 13:12.700
the very idea of either of us

13:12.700 --> 13:15.100
doing battle for big tobacco—

13:15.500 --> 13:18.600
an industry which
systematically kills people…

13:21.900 --> 13:24.672
I hope they give you
a lot of money, then.

13:25.200 --> 13:27.600
Of course,
it would be worth it.

13:28.000 --> 13:31.700
Mm. And here you are
at Crane, Poole & Schmidt.

13:32.400 --> 13:34.560
I don't need to apologize
for myself.

13:34.600 --> 13:35.900
No,

13:35.900 --> 13:38.060
Not when it's easier to just walk out the door.
–I didn't walk—

13:38.100 --> 13:39.400
Yes, you did.

13:40.600 --> 13:43.100
Yes, you did.

13:45.600 --> 13:46.900
You know what?

13:47.900 --> 13:50.276
I think
that you have changed, Alan.

13:51.200 --> 13:54.100
Your eyes look… Deadened.

13:55.400 --> 13:58.660
They say that a man's passion
is the first thing to die as he ages,

13:58.700 --> 14:02.760
so I suppose that should make it easier
 for me to be around you,

14:02.800 --> 14:04.800
because it was your passion

14:04.800 --> 14:06.900
that I so fell in love with.

14:19.000 --> 14:21.100
Your offer is rejected…

14:27.700 --> 14:29.300
so you can leave now.

14:31.400 --> 14:32.500
Okay, Alan.

14:36.700 --> 14:38.500
We'll be seeing you, then.

15:03.300 --> 15:05.860
He first started smoking cigarettes
when he was 11.

15:05.900 --> 15:07.660
He smoked
the defendant's brand?

15:07.700 --> 15:09.060
Mainly that brand, yes.

15:09.100 --> 15:11.560
And your father smoked
cigarettes for how long?

15:11.600 --> 15:12.700
Over 50 years.

15:12.700 --> 15:15.960
Maureen, at some point, your
father certainly had to know

15:16.000 --> 15:17.782
that smoking causes cancer.

15:17.900 --> 15:20.100
He tried to quit
so many times.

15:20.400 --> 15:22.860
He was desperate to quit,
but he was addicted.

15:22.900 --> 15:25.160
Sometimes he could
go months without,

15:25.200 --> 15:26.460
but he'd always
start up again.

15:26.500 --> 15:29.200
He just couldn't—
<i>–Oh, baby.</i>

15:29.200 --> 15:32.300
<i>Ohh, that feels so good.</i>

15:32.300 --> 15:34.100
<i>Don't stop.</i>

15:34.100 --> 15:35.600
<i>Ohh!</i>

15:36.900 --> 15:37.800
Hello?

15:37.800 --> 15:39.500
–Denny.
–It's my doctor.

15:39.500 --> 15:41.500
–I don't care.
–Shh.

15:42.400 --> 15:43.960
I did that,
but it still doesn't work.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.500
Get off the phone now.

15:46.600 --> 15:48.580
I gotta get off
the phone now.

15:50.400 --> 15:51.300
What?

15:53.400 --> 15:54.500
I'm sorry.

15:56.900 --> 16:00.398
And a-at some point,
your father did get lung cancer.

16:00.400 --> 16:01.900
11 years ago.

16:02.500 --> 16:05.800
He fought it. He—
He had one lung removed.

16:06.000 --> 16:07.800
He did everything that…

16:09.600 --> 16:11.300
But, um…

16:11.700 --> 16:14.100
eventually
it went to his brain.

16:14.200 --> 16:17.500
In the end, it was, uh,
a miserable…

16:17.900 --> 16:19.900
excruciating death.

16:20.800 --> 16:24.100
